doc.title: NISA data continues to trend positively yoy, but with a slight pull back in the allocation to domestic equities
doc.source_uri: 2025-08-31/Japan Weekly Kickstart NISA data continues to trend positively yoy but with a slight pull back in the allocation to dome_2025-08-31

passages.text: Top sectors: Non- Ferrous Metals, Mining Bottom sectors: Retail, Other Products

In this week's Japan Weekly Kickstart, we focus on the latest NISA data from the Japan Securities Dealers Association (JSDA). In terms of value traded based on data from 10 major brokers, up to July 2025, NISA ytd value traded continued to trend above last year's cumulative run- rate (Exhibit 1), topping ¥9tr. However, the traded value of domestic equities fell from a high of 40% Jan- Mar CY 2025 (LINK) back down to 38% Jan- July CY 2025 (Exhibit 2).

Index level pause remains in place as some profit- taking continues: NKY and TPX are now - 2.3% and - 1.5% respectively below their all- time- highs, with RSIs back around 60 for both indices. Many clients have welcomed the recent pull- back, but we still believe that an incremental positive catalyst will be required to justify further multiple expansion from here.

Positive developments in the inbound M&A thematic: It was reported last week (LINK) that Taiwan's Yageo expects to receive Foreign Exchange and Foreign Trade Act (EFETA) approval regarding its US \(740mn bid for sensor manufacturer Shibaura Electronics. Yageo's revised offer of ¥7,130 per share was 15% higher than a rival offer by Japan's Minebea Mitsumi. As we argued in Japan Portfolio Strategy: Positioning for Japan's new wave of M&A- related alpha opportunities (9 June 2025), we believe that increased M&A activity in Japan (including successful inbound M&A) is an essential part of the next phase of the Japanese equities market rally. More M&A will drive more sector consolidation, which in turn should lead to higher ROEs and PBRs.

Foreigner and Domestics were net sellers while Individuals were net sellers: According to the latest data from the TSE, for the week 18- 22 July, Foreigners and Domestic Institutions net sold - ¥198bn and - ¥156bn of TSE Prime cash equities respectively, while Individuals net bought ¥150bn.

In terms of value traded based on data from 10 major brokers, up to July 2025, NISA ytd value traded continued to trend above last year's cumulative run- rate (Exhibit 1), topping ¥9tr. However, the percentage traded value of domestic equities fell from a high of 40% Jan- Mar CY 2025 (LINK) back down to 38% Jan- July CY 2025 (Exhibit 2). Nevertheless, of the remaining 59% of NISA traded value involved in investment trusts, we think it is reasonable to assume that a meaningful percentage of this activity has also been focused on domestic equities- related products so far this year.

Our original analysis which has now been integrated into the Japan Weekly Kickstart format focuses on sector and thematic performance of the more liquid portion of the Japanese equities market. This is defined as any Japanese stocks that trade over US\$20mn advt. We believe that a significant number of our clients have liquidity constraints which require them to limit their stand- alone positions to this particular universe. By our calculations, there are 249 stocks in Japan that trade above this liquidity threshold as of Mar 31 2025.

We have sub- divided this universe into 45 equal weighted indices that focus on either MSCI- defined sectors and sub- sectors, or areas of thematic focus that stretch across multiple sectors (such as High Dividend Yield or Gaming). For these thematic indices, we have relied either on quantitative measures and/or GS Equity analyst input on component selection. We hope to expand the number of indices over time and would welcome client feedback on any areas of thematic interest we should focus on.

We track the performance of the equal- weighted sector, sub- sector and thematic indices over time and also measure the spread between the best- performing and the worst- performing stocks within the index. For example, Exhibit 24 illustrates both the volatility of the mean weekly performance in the liquid SPE index (the dark blue line), and the weekly Best- Worst spreads within the index (the light blue cloud).
Exhibit 24: SPE index 52 week equal-weighted cumulative weekly performance and best-worst spreads
Source: FactSet, Data compiled by Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research
The criteria we have used in our analysis of the liquid Japanese equities market can be summarized as follows:

- Total universe consists of Japanese stocks with a 6-month advt of over US\$20mn (249 stocks as of March 31 2025).- The universe will be refreshed every 6 months.- Indices are all equal-weighted.- Index component selection is based on MSCI sector and sub-sector definitions, quantitative factors and/or GS single-stock Equity Analyst guidance.- The same stock can appear in multiple indices.- The Best-Worst spread is based on the difference between the best performing and worst performing component within each index.- The first 12 months of trading of any new listing are not included in the index performance.
We anticipate that the number of indices will be adjusted over time and would welcome any client feedback on other areas within the liquid Japan equities universe we should be focused on.
